</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fabbz>Fabbz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 78<br> <font color=#333333>(1/1/03 10:56:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm46.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=175.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_mad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: ...</span><hr size=1> well, i'm probably gonna get flamed for being the one voice in disagreement here...but here's my thoughts.<br>
<br>
basically everyone is saying that EQ was designed to have options.  you should be able to advance in a guild, or in a group, or with friends on weekends, or solo...whatever you feel like doing.  the problem people are having is that PoP is simply not designed like that, instead it is a guild-centered expansion where most of the content (nearly all of the much-vaunted &quot;dynamic content&quot;) requires mutiple groups...and as we know, if you need 3+ groups to do something that means you usually need a guild type orginization, wether or not you actually make it an official guild.<br>
<br>
here's the thing though...noone is forcing you to level.  PoP wasn't specifically designed to screw over the casual player, it was designed to give a new path to the top-end guilds that had already been there and done that all through Luclin.  certainly some of the content is appropriate for the casual player, but as you progress through PoP it becomes totally raid/guild centered.  in fact i think verant and sony went out of their way to open the planes to people who aren't in raid guilds, why else would those quests be there?  they could have, very easily, made the flag only accessable to those who kill the mobs, but they didn't, because they understood that the casual player needed a chance to get there too.  and yes, i understand how time consuming those quests are.<br>
<br>
i suppose i just have to question anyone who can honestly ask why, if they play 1 hour a week, and someone else plays 35 hours a week, why that person should be farther along in the game.  noone is forcing people to proceed into PoP or to dash to level 65.  the policy seems fairly direct to me...the more time you put in the more results you will get.  however, the amount of time is your choice, knowing that you sacrifice the results by spending less time working toward them.<br>
<br>
the notes about how insanely simple XP grinding is in pop seems to fall into this explanation when you consider one simple fact.  to most raid-guild 30+ hour a week players xp grinding is BORING, incredibly boring, most would go as far as to call it &quot;work&quot; as opposed to the &quot;fun&quot; of raids.  easy and fast ways to get xp are a simple, efficient way to get these people to 65 and topped off on AA's that will kick them into the 3rd and 4th tier planes.  basically if you can stand the 40 hours a week of mind-numbing chain pulls in valor then you are obviously one of these hardcore raid people, so you need to get done and back to raiding as fast as possible, and that means faster xp.  it's a bone they threw to the raid guilds who suddenly had their &quot;uber&quot; players 5 levels too low and 30 points behind in AA's.<br>
<br>
the thing is, to the casual player...this all means nothing at all, zippo.  if anything it is a benefit, there are now places that, if you so desired, you could get to 65 and many AA's much faster than ever before.  if you do not want to be the 24/7 raid type (which seems to be the general consensus of people here) then you basically trade a real life (40 hour a week raid guilds ARE those people's lives) for not having the phattest lewt or access to the most uber zones.<br>
<br>
the argument that people will quit EQ in any real numbers because they can't advance in PoP has no grounding at all.  how many guilds didn't get into VP in kunark era?  how many killed AOW in velious' times?  Vex Thal?  there have always been areas that the &quot;casual player&quot; has been restricted from.  and well, bluntly, sony isn't bankrupt yet...so i have to assume that not that many quit over it.  in fact, it would seem logical to me that the exact opposite is true.  people would quit in masses WITHOUT this high-end content accessable to only a few.  if every person could log in for an hour a week and get access to a new plane then all of pop would have been done by the big guilds already and they'd have nothing to look foward to.<br>
<br>
geez, i think i started a book or something.  didn't think that would be so long <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fabbz>Fabbz</A> at: 1/1/03 10:57:14 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=shazar23>Shazar23</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 489<br> <font color=#333333>(1/1/03 1:58:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm46.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=175.topic&index=37>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ...</span><hr size=1> &quot;Massively multiplayer&quot; in mmorpg implies a need for social interaction.  I think you are in a very small minority in thinking you can be 65th level and still be effective in EQ as a totally independent player.  The game requires a lot of teamwork to be successful.  Guilds are the most efficient tools available for mustering competent raid forces to accomplish high end objectives.  A guild is a friends list with its own chat channel.<br>
